			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">The Nature of the Twist<a name="5392"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 13 03 8:32 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>
<br />

<br />
Good morning fellow musicians, minstrels, rockstars and
<br />
impressarios!
<br />

<br />
My topic today is about twisting songs.  There is an aspect
<br />
of twisting songs that I rarely ever see discussed, and I
<br />
believe that applying it well can have some tremendous
<br />
result.
<br />

<br />
I call it simply, &quot;skipping a beat&quot;.
<br />

<br />
It is, however, very complicated to explain, and probably to
<br />
learn as well.  Fortunately, we are bards, and therefore used
<br />
to everything being complicated and difficult.
<br />

<br />
To understand what one wants to acheive when skipping a
<br />
beat, one must understand the nature of the twist.  A lot of
<br />
people have been limiting themselves to a 3-4 song twist.
<br />
There is a way to get around that to effectively increase the
<br />
number of songs one is playing.  First, let us divide songs into
<br />
two categories.  There are songs that affect the aspect of 
<br />
the fight; mostly consisting of hastes, slows, stat buffs, and
<br />
the like.  Then there are songs that pulse one effect, I need
<br />
to come up with a better name for them I know, mostly being
<br />
the stuns, heals, runes.
<br />

<br />
Let's say that it's been decided we were going to play a 6
<br />
song cycle.  In that 6 song cycle, we're going to have 4
<br />
songs up at once all the time, and 6 songs up most of the
<br />
time.  The two songs that are going to be fading will be the
<br />
heal/mana and niv's, so you'll have to look at those as 300hp
<br />
every 6 ticks, depending on on level etc.
<br />

<br />
When making up twists, the one thing to remind yourself is,
<br />
&quot;is this song important to have up at ALL times during a fight,
<br />
or will it still be good if it's up most of the time during a fight?&quot;
<br />

<br />
If you adapt well to a fight then this technique will definitely
<br />
suit you, since it gives you more options, in my humble
<br />
opinion.
<br />

<br />
Hopefully this will spark some discussions, and someone can
<br />
explain it clearer to the people who will reply with &quot;huh?&quot;...
<br />

<br />
Astuce Subterfuge
<br />
Elysiam's Triad
<br />
Innoruuk Server
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
